{
  "text": "Given the muscarinic nature of NB actions [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and the hypothesized ionic basis of V,,, fluctuations, we further propose that NB-mediated modification of V, fluctuations results from muscarinic blockade of spontaneous K+ currents, allowing intermixed rapid depolarizations and Cl--mediated hyperpolarizations to continue uninterrupted. Two tests of our hypotheses are immediately apparent: first, pharmacological blockade of K+ channels should produce effects similar to those of NB stimulation; second, blockade of Cl-channels should produce predictable modifications of spontaneous and NB-mediated effects, since Cl-currents might normally act to retard depolarization. Since the WCR technique allows rapid diffusion of pharmacological agents into the cell interior [CITATION_3] we attempted to test these hypotheses through modifications of the WCR pipette solutions.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "10048883",
